text:
happy kwanzaa!

are you familiar with kwanzaa?  it is a nonreligious celebration of family and optimism for the new year.  nice for us all to celebrate!

kwanzaa uses a kinara (similar to a menorah) to light a candle each day celebrating the seven principles - unity, self-determination, collective responsibility, cooperative economics, purpose, creativity, and faith.  good principles to reflect on, end the year with, and begin the new year â¤ï¸

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
do you trust me? i know you may not know me very well, but i promise you i would not steer you wrong.
.
these are all real pictures of real women {my personal real friends} who have made real changes. changes you can clearly see on the outside, and huge changes on the inside which you canâ€™t physically see.
.
we work together every day to support, uplift and motivate each other to practice healthy living every day. some days are better than others because we have found a for life lifestyleâ€” 
and thatâ€™s real life!
.
but we always have our community to help us through the hard days {and sometimes seasons}, we always have a plan that we know works for the long term, and we always have each otherâ€™s backs!
.
these are women who decided
â€¢enough of the quick fixes
â€¢enough of the yo-yo dieting
â€¢enough of thinking they didnâ€™t deserve to be a priority .
and they made a change
.
and you can too! make 2019 the year you decided to go for itâ€” 
go for those changes for goodâ€”
for you!
.
and know when you are ready to make the choice, you donâ€™t have to be on the journey alone!
.
.

text:
this was a serious business, it was actually backed by goldman sachs, but it crashed and went bankrupt because the gamers themselves who weren't cheating became enraged basically that these other people were doing, they put so much pressure on the gaming companies.

they put so much pressure on the video game companies, that they decided to basically ban gold-farming, which killed bannon's business, but it awakened him to the power of what he called "rootless white males" who spend all their time online. and five years later when bannon wound up at breitbart, he resolved to try and attract those people over to breitbart because he thought they could be radicalized in a kind of populist, nationalist way. and the way that bannon did that, the bridge between the angry abusive gamers and breitbart and pepe was milo yiannopoulous, who bannon discovered and hired to be breitbart's tech editor.

from the time i met him in 2011, he's had exactly the same politics. the same stuff you heard from trump, you saw on the campaign trail. what he was looking for was a vessel because nobody in republican washington believed in these kinds of ideas. the whole trend in the republican party was toward liberalizing immigration laws, passing comprehensive immigration reform. he was against it.

joshua green
devil's bargain: steve bannon, donald trump, and the storming of the presidency

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
in his first post-white house interviews, steve bannon, the rightwing ideologue who helped propel donald trump to the white house, made clear that he had no intention of going quietly. - iâ€™ve got my hands back on my weapons, the former white house chief strategist, who returned as executive chairman of breitbart news late friday afternoon, told the weekly standard. - i built a f***ing machine at breitbart. and now iâ€™m about to go back, knowing what i know, and weâ€™re about to rev that machine up. and rev it up we will do.

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

just hours after his departure from the trump administration became public, breitbart, whose traffic and advertising have fallen significantly since trumpâ€™s election, trumpeted the return of their â€œpopulist heroâ€ on its homepage. - the populist-nationalist movement got a lot stronger today, breitbart editor-in-chief alex marlow said in the publicationâ€™s announcement post. - breitbart gained an executive chairman with his finger on the pulse of the trump agenda.

the fall of steve bannon is a win for the globalists. but will it last?

also on friday, the once-again head of breitbart told bloomberg news: - if thereâ€™s any confusion out there, let me clear it up: iâ€™m leaving the white house and going to war for trump against his opponents â€“ on capitol hill, in the media, and in corporate america.

the 63-year-old also retains the backing of hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. the pair met on wednesday to plot their future plans, bloomberg reported.

julia carrie wong
the guardian

text:
my idea of a nice hawaiian punch bowl - some #lebaneseredhash over some #goldengoat (relates back to maui wowie) dreamy and redolent of ginger. damn, hawaiian punch was the bomb diggity over snowcones. violent punching aside, or do we need to #metoo the intimate partner violence depicted in those cartoons? can i like hawaiian punch while protesting the jovial yet sinister depiction of the creepy little bully repeatedly dishing out blows to the head of his target? #ambivalentmuch a person who seems to exhibit signs of #cte i might add. yeah no. a straw hat and tourist shirt doesn't make your punch cool. i feel like ashton would sit him down and say, 'bro - too far, man...' and now we have to live with things like kardashians (omg stop making us contour it looks awful in profile) and juice bars. look like a clone. get a non-beverage, a bioplastic cup of fastwalking superiority to go. no. i want the stuff on the bourgeois table. if you're serving me a green beverage it'd better be lime kool-aid. not some kale-flavored colonic decontamination concoction masquerading as a proper meal. .
.
what's the word on hawaiian punch? tainted love or don't be a chucklehead it's delicious and no cartoons never hurt nobody whatsoevers. .
.
.
i may or may not have had a bunch of dark chocolate which is possibly the source of enough caffeine to make the squirrel squad in my head react like meth house rats to the whole ethics of beverages line of inquiry. and one final tangent: diabetes. we drank a lot of packages of that stuff. sure is something to ponder going forward. do i really need more food dye in my life? #hawaiianpunch #eatclean #oldfolksmoke #coololdstuff #meditationart #cannabis 
#cannabisismymedicine @wave_maker_ Â©2018

it took insane amount of courage to post a picture of myself without makeup. for some people it may not be a big deal but for someone who has suffered from bullying and had an extremly tough time loving herself, it is a quite a big deal to post a picture of something that was once her greatest insecurity. by no means am i implying that there is something wrong with the idea of covering up or doing makeup. its has helped me through my toughest days and made me think that i finally look pretty. read that sentence again. i said that it made me "think" i look pretty. which brings me to my main point that its all in the mind. once i started looking at myself in the mirror from a new prespective i realized that i am beyond beautiful even with or without the luxury of makeup. my motive is to make other individuals realize the same thing. this can only be done if the definition of beauty itself is altered in our minds.

text:
when i had to make the decision to stay in new zealand for longer i resented the circumstances around it, and it felt like forever.

but now thereâ€™s hardly any time left.

itâ€™s so nice to be here. in a place where everything wrong that happened to me over there takes hardly any explanation to people.

in a place where what you see is more like what you get, instead of what you see being some carefully crafted mirage designed to conceal how ugly the situation really is.

it was driven home while i was here; the entire nation visibly in mourning for a murdered english tourist, from people in the street to the prime-minister.

how could this happen here, this isnâ€™t who we want to be. we are so sorry. we offered no excuses, looked long and hard at ourselves, resolved to do better, to let the story live on to that end.

it doesnâ€™t happen that way other way around. when our women die over there. it barely makes a ripple in a society with an undertow so vicious you have to be caught by it before you believe it could ever exist.

i canâ€™t remember if i wrote about the kiwi woman i met by chance at the wedding i went to. whose colleagues in london murdered her cat and draped it over her doorway when she made a formal complaint about racial discrimination at her workplace. she came back here, of course.

i canâ€™t remember if i wrote about the kiwi woman hired into a role as a producer only to be given admin and low level editing work, whose employers exploited the two-years they have to harass and violate human rights at will in the workplace to humiliate her until she quit. she was only hired to be a pretty thing. she stayed over there, she had enough industry contacts to.

i canâ€™t remember if i wrote about the kiwi programme manager, who took a male junior staff member with her into a meeting with uk stakeholders. she was the only woman in the room. the men addressed all their questions to the young man. he walked out of the meeting in disgust. they spoke to her then.
.
â€œi hear from a lot of ex-pat kiwis with stories from the uk like yours.â€ tell me about it.

iâ€™d tell you about it.

but i wake up every morning with these thick hands tightly around my throat.

itâ€™s so nice to be here. in a place where everything wrong that happened to me over there takes hardly any explanation to people.

in a place where what you see is more like what you get, instead of what you see being some carefully crafted mirage designed to conceal how ugly the situation really is.

it was driven home while i was here; the entire nation visibly in mourning for a murdered english tourist, from people in the street to the prime-minister.

how could this happen here, this isnâ€™t who we want to be. we are so sorry. we offered no excuses, looked long and hard at ourselves, resolved to do better, to let the story live on to that end.

it doesnâ€™t happen that way other way around. when our women die over there. it barely makes a ripple in a society with an undeow so vicious you have to be caught by it before you believe it could ever exist.

i canâ€™t remember if i wrote about the kiwi woman i met by chance at the wedding i went to. whose colleagues in london murdered her cat and draped it over her doorway when she made a formal complaint about racial discrimination at her workplace. she came back here, of course.

i canâ€™t remember if i wrote about the kiwi woman hired into a role as a producer only to be given admin and low level editing work, whose employers exploited the two-years they have to harass and violate human rights at will in the workplace to humiliate her until she quit. she was only hired to be a pretty thing. she stayed over there, she had enough industry contacts to.

i canâ€™t remember if i wrote about the kiwi programme manager, who took a male junior staff member with her into a meeting with uk stakeholders. she was the only woman in the room. the men addressed all their questions to the young man. he walked out of the meeting in disgust. they spoke to her then.
.
â€œi hear from a lot of ex-pat kiwis with stories from the uk like yours.â€ tell me about it.

iâ€™d tell you about it.

but i wake up every morning with these thick hands tightly around my throat.

coming of age in a culture that demands women be as small, quiet, and compliant as possibleâ€”like a porcelain dove that will also have sex with youâ€”writer and humorist lindy west quickly discovered that she was anything but. 
from a painfully shy childhood in which she tried, unsuccessfully, to hide her big body and even bigger opinions; to her public war with stand-up comedians over rape jokes; to her struggle to convince herself, and then the world, that fat people have value; to her accidental activism and never-ending battle royale with internet trolls, lindy narrates her life with a blend of humor and pathos that manages to make a trip to the abortion clinic funny and wring tears out of a story about diarrhea.

with inimitable good humor, vulnerability, and boundless charm, lindy boldly shares how to survive in a world where not all stories are created equal and not all bodies are treated with equal respect, and how to weather hatred, loneliness, harassment, and lossâ€”and walk away laughing. shrill provocatively dissects what it means to become self-aware the hard way, to go from wanting to be silent and invisible to earning a living defending the silenced in all caps.

text:
summing up 2018ğŸ˜…
i saw a couple of friends do this cool move in their wheelchairs where they put their arms behind and balance on two wheels. it looked so cool i thought i'd give it a go. then i remembered i don't have triceps so instead, i fell back and struck this awesome pose.Â 
i have to say, best place i've found to fall over like this - canada. i was immediately surrounded by 10 lovely guys who lifted me back inğŸ¥° ğŸ’•worst place - good old new zealand. the one time i fell out, i lay crumpled on the ground and a truckie drove past, hooted and gave me the thumbs up lol... typical 'do it yourself' kiwi attitude! ğŸ¥ğŸ¤”ğŸ¥´sometimes i kinda wish people would offer to help but doesn't happen much here, and i guess it's because many are scared i'll be offended because i can 'do it my-bloody-self'. truth is, sometimes in life, a hand is what we need, and if anyone ever offers to help me, even with getting my chair in and out of my car or grabbing a can off the supermarket shelf instead of me throwing something at it to knock it down... i'll usually gratefully accept help. if i'm feeling ultra independent that day, i'll decline but always with a smile and a thank you, because i realise they are 1. trying to be helpful 2. totally out of their comfort zone and up for abuse from what could be 'an angry cripple'. people just want to help, it's rare here, not because we aren't a caring bunch, we are, but we are also terrified of offending people. my advice, ask someone like me if they'd like a hand, if they tell you to 'f' off, don't take it personally, just know you tried to help, you have a beautiful heart and although your kindness wasn't needed, it may well be next time. #pose #fallen #tryingtobecool #fail #funny #laughter #smile #weird #help #redhair #redhead #wheelchair #spinalcordinjury #wheels #summer #newzealand #grass #2018

36. cate blanchett is an actor, director and feminist. she has become internationally famous for her iconic films such as elizabeth. she has won many awards for her acting such as: baftas, golden globe awards, and academy awards to name a few. the main reason she is on here though is for her feminism. she led a protest at cannes as only one woman had won the top prize every other year it had gone to a man. she led a protest where 82 women stood on the steps to show the number of women that have been featured in the 71 year history. she has also made a speech at cannes  about how it should be more equal and they need to work towards that. on top of all that she has also been very open and brave about the sexual misconduct she suffered from harvey weinstein. all in all i think she is a talented and brave feminist. #feminist #feminism #equality  #equalist #influencer #influential #influentialwomen #influentialwoman #inspiration #inspirational #inspirationalwomen #inspirationalwomanâ¤ï¸ #inspirationalwoman #cateblanchett #actor #director #metoo #timesup #cannes #cannesfilmfestival

- bannon got it immediately. he believes in the whole andrew breitbart doctrine that politics is downstream from culture, so to change politics you need to change culture. and fashion trends are a useful proxy for that. trump is like a pair of uggs, or crocs, basically. so how do you get from people thinking â€˜ugh. totally uglyâ€™ to the moment when everyone is wearing them? that was the inflection point he was looking for.

is what cambridge analytica does akin to bullying? - i think itâ€™s worse than bullying, christopher wylie says. - because people donâ€™t necessarily know itâ€™s being done to them. at least bullying respects the agency of people because they know. so itâ€™s worse, because if you do not respect the agency of people, anything that youâ€™re doing after that point is not conducive to a democracy. and fundamentally, information warfare is not conducive to democracy.

millions of peopleâ€™s personal information was stolen and used to target them in ways they wouldnâ€™t have seen, and couldnâ€™t have known about, by a mercenary outfit, cambridge analytica, who, wylie says, â€œwould work for anyoneâ€. who would pitch to russian oil companies. would they subvert elections abroad on behalf of foreign governments?

it occurs to me to ask wylie this one night. - yes.

nato or non-nato? - either. i mean theyâ€™re mercenaries. theyâ€™ll work for pretty much anyone who pays.

itâ€™s an incredible revelation. it also encapsulates all of the problems of outsourcing â€“ at a global scale, with added cyberweapons. and in the middle of it all are the public â€“ our intimate family connections, our â€œlikesâ€, our crumbs of personal data, all sucked into a swirling black hole thatâ€™s expanding and growing and is now owned by a politically motivated billionaire.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
when i was 9 years old, i was raped. recently, i told my family in a fit of anger that was not the best way, but the only way i could do it. this person had me for 2 years, over 40 times and i've just begun my healing. i want people.to know that coming out to your tribe is the most important thing to do. and if you cannot see anyone, you can talk to me. after more than 20 years i learned that all that bottled rage was the cause of this. it hurts people, you the people around and these kinds of rapists feel little remorse for what they've done.

i've decided this is not something to be ashamed of. i refuse to let this ruin me. and if any of you have a similar experience, don't wait, because the pain can be long and relentless. and most of all, there is no shame in what you went through. 
#metoo
#speakup
#aintnoshame

text:
a few months later, in autumn 2013, wylie met steve bannon. at the time, he was editor-in-chief of breitbart, which he had brought to britain to support his friend nigel farage in his mission to take britain out of the european union.

what was he like? - smart, says wylie. - interesting. really interested in ideas. heâ€™s the only straight man iâ€™ve ever talked to about intersectional feminist theory. he saw its relevance straightaway to the oppressions that conservative, young white men feel.

wylie meeting bannon was the moment petrol was poured on a flickering flame. wylie lives for ideas. he speaks 19 to the dozen for hours at a time. he had a theory to prove. and at the time, this was a purely intellectual problem. politics was like fashion, he told bannon.

carole cadwalladr
the guardian

text:
cambridge analytica, which was shut down earlier this year following an investigation by the observer, was the political marketing firm headed by trumpâ€™s former key adviser, steve bannon, and owned by hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer. it also used user information obtained without authorisation in early 2014 â€“ including cultural preferences such as fashion and music â€“ to create a system that could single out voters in order to expose them to specific political advertising.

prior to the companyâ€™s role on trumpâ€™s election campaign, wylie had been its director of research. recalling his first meeting with bannon, he explained how fashion was one of the many things they examined, along with â€œjudith butler, foucault and nature of our fractured selfâ€. he said the pair discussed the difference between crocs and chanelâ€™s little black dress as analogous for the fashion spectrum â€“ which would become a blueprint for how the firm used fashion preferences later on.

wylie went onto to criticise the fashion industry for creating a â€œpre-existing cultural foundation which allowed the alt-right to grow over that time periodâ€. he conceded that while cambridge analytica â€œexploited the cultural narratives that the fashion and culture industry put outâ€, the fashion industry was responsible for creating those cultural narratives in the first place. he added: â€œwe need new narratives in culture, and to do a better job of showing more diversityâ€ in order to direct politics along a different route.

according to the data obtained (the majority of which came from us users), certain fans of american denim brands such as wrangler, hollister and lee jeans could be more closely linked to low levels of openness and mistrust â€“ and therefore more likely to engage with pro-trump messaging.

morwenna ferrier
the guardian

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

text:
as 2019 approaches, we want to reflect on our event, â€œcreating spacesâ€ which addressed #violenceagainstwomen in our community (inspired by the global project of the same name by @oxfamcanada which is helping in 6 countries abroad on this topic). we was a great success, and we effectively created a safe space for a moderated, educational conversation on gender-based violence. 
we are proud to #believesurvivors & are thrilled to reflect on the many victories for survivors this year, starting with the â€œsilence breakersâ€ (time person of the year 2017) to the womenâ€™s usa gymnastics team for their victory to the #metoo campaign in general, among many others. we are also reflecting on losses that continue to occur when people in positions of power perpetuate the problem of #genderbasedviolence. 
going into #2019, we are ready to take on the good fight. human rights for human kind. 
#womensrightsarehumanrights

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
at a hearing before the senate judiciary committee, christopher wylie described discussions at the company about suppressing the vote, exploiting racial tensions, and testing campaign slogans in 2014 for use in the 2016 election. - one of the things that did provoke me to leave was the beginnings of discussions of voter disengagement, i have seen documents reference and i recall conversations that it was intended to focus on african-american voters. the company learned that there were segments of the population that responded to messages like â€˜drain the swampâ€™ or images of border walls or indeed paranoia about the â€˜deep stateâ€™ that werenâ€™t necessarily reflected in mainstream polling or mainstream political discourse that steve bannon was interested in to help build his movement.

jon sharman
the independent

cambridge analyticaâ€™s parent company, scl, had won contracts with the us state department and was pitching to the pentagon, and wylie was genuinely freaked out. - itâ€™s insane, he told me one night. - the company has created psychological profiles of 230 million americans. and now they want to work with the pentagon? itâ€™s like nixon on steroids.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates suppoed by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

many moons ago, each of us embarked on an unfamiliar journey. not knowing if it would lead us to fulfillment. yet still, we had faith. we hit rock bottom too many times to count and prayed that better days were ahead.
our road to ascension was a tortuous one. it brought the darkest depths of our souls to the light. but never once did we forget how hard we'd have to fight to survive facing our shadows in plain sight.it took everything we had to make it through. to make that sparkle in our eyes reignite.
yet we made it.
we went with the flow of life.
then we became the flow,
and took flight.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
merry christmas and happy holidays to you all! 
for those that are not celebrating christmas i still wish you great holidays. this time of the year is not so happy and cheerful for all of us. one of the contributing factors in my opinion is social media. it is a constant reminder of all the things that you miss in you own life. social media does not display the reality, it is a false reality, but still you sit and compare yourself to everyone. i just wanted to remind you that you are great. you are enough just the way you are. you are strong and getting through all of you struggles day by day.  the pictures above are just a small summery of some of the things we should say to ourselves.
take time to affirm and appreciate yourself everyday.

text:
take a good look at the 33rd! edition of the #economist telling you in your face the state of the staged world in the upcoming episode of this ritualistic reality show that we have all unwillingly taken part in.
what does a stork usually carry in a bag? yeah, a baby...only this time the "product" has a barcode and a serial number on it as it is shipped from a supposed poor region (poor weirdo ghandi) of the world to the western land of the electric cars...someone should get on that serial number to decode it...and that vitruvian man with a night vision/virtual reality gear on...
â€¢
all the satanic mirrored spells aside, "putin's pipelines" is written right above the depiction of the four horsemen of the apocalypse to come at the end of the world symbolizing conquest, war, famine, and plague/death...
â€¢
i don't even wanna talk about the baseball, the "cell"phone, that hemp leaf and that fucking scale with 4=5 people on each side, 2+2=5 concept from 1984 programming written by a bbc whore of a mason with a fake name george whorewell...
â€¢ 
there is a ton of symbolism, like the one-eyed black and white panda (china) sitting between putin-trump, the duality of the two voting boxes representing the fake political systems with south african and indian flags (with british ties that claimed independence) on them as opposed to that brexit bulldog, the pinocchio with an arrow on his face, the indian elephant tusk going up like a chart maybe representing the booming economy/tech of india, all those written headlines up there with as clear as daylight numeralogy attached to these letters which i can't even wanna start looking into anymore, the #metoo tattoo, that amarillo that symbolizes protection and boundaries with its protective shell reminding us to protect ourselves and a lot more hidden layers of esoteric meanings and geometry behind this...
â€¢
many regards to my brother @loong_distance for exchanging ideas and decoding techniques...love how a healthy mind thinks...
â€¢
p.s. i dunno who are the two bitches at the bottom, i can't make anything out of ghandi with that salt-making device and can't read what's written above that elephant under that satellite looking thingy .

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

tonight is our last in tel aviv for this winter trip. luckily for us, the 25th of december is like any other day here, which means the bars are open and the cocktails are flowing. at the same time, weâ€™d love to spread a little bit of christmas cheer from one of our favorite establishments from the past weekâ€”thank you to both bar manager @morben29 and
bartender @eldar_gabay92 for making @223tlv feel like a home away from home. using several flavor components representative of israeli culture and agriculture, @arielleizgold built an incredible concoction to battle the scorching summer heat and cozy up with during the cooler winter months. his tlv heat is a year-round crowd pleaser at @223tlv as a result, and presented as the perfect christmas present. while weâ€™re leaving for barcelona in the morning, we have plenty more to share from our time in tel aviv over the coming weeks. for now, check out the recipe below, stay warm, and have a merry christmas.
-
tlv heat

40 ml ouzo
10 ml elderflower liqueur @stgermaindrinks
15 ml fig jam
20 ml lime juice
20 ml orange juice
2 dashes sheba tincture

garnish: dehydrated orange, dehydrated lime, sesame candy, sprig of mint, and sprinkle over top with powdered sugar

glassware: enamel red & white mug

method: shake briefly and dirty strain into the mug. fill with crushed ice, garnish as above, and add a straw for easy imbibing.

creator: ariel leizgold @arielleizgold, owner & master mixologist of @223tlv
-
a job well done to @arielleizgold and the whole @223tlv team for building a craft cocktail program thatâ€™s both the first and longest-running of its kind in israel. thank you for the incredible experience. #keepitcrafted

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text: christmas can be hard for many. my heart goes out to all the people who are struggling beneath the surface these holidays. whether if itâ€™s a lost loved one, depression, a broken home, anxiety, an eating disorder, a broken marriage, abuse, addiction.... itâ€™s hard to find joy when your heart is hurting. remember this truth today - â€œwhen my smile gets a little forced, when i feel tired upon waking and when i start to bully myself within my own mind. i will try to remember whose birthday i am celebrating today (christâ€™s), and see past the tinsel, turkey and trimmings. when jesus left his stable and entered into his ministry, his focus was not solely on the happy, the blessed and the ones who had it all together. he focused on lepers and sinners, the poor and helpless. this christmas i will remember jesus as the light. he is a light which is made to help those who suffer darkness.â€ jesus taught us all to not forget those who are suffering or facing a difficult time in life, and that it's not what we get that defines us but what we give to others that tells the real story about who we are. merry christmas everyone. if you're one of those hurting at christmas this year, know you aren't forgotten and that others care about you. you are loved. you are not alone. â¤ï¸

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

shecan: the scene presenter salma el-wardany

the scene is onÂ  bbc radio london with evening shows from monday 26 november as six new presenters take over from 8-10pm, fronted by six presenters with backgrounds from across londonâ€™s cultural, music, comedy and spoken word worlds.
#bbcradiolondon editor davidrobey, says:â€œthe scene will be a platform for londonâ€™s community arts, entertainment and cultural activities, featuring new talent and emerging artists, performers and creators. #aurie, claira, judi, jasmine, salma and lionheart have first-hand experience and knowledge of whatâ€™s happening in londonâ€™s creative and diverse communities which they will bring to listeners every weekday evening on the scene.â€ alt wanted to find out more about writer, poet, spoken word artist and tedx speaker salma el-wardany.Â pictured salma and co-host #lionheart.

alt: woman are being given a platform and the focus on women has catapulted, do you think we can sustain this movement and can it be credited to the #timesup and #metoo movements?

salma: i think it would be unfair of the efforts of feminists over the decades to solely credit the current shifts to just those two movements, especially since they are movements that have been dominated by white, letâ€™s be honest, rich, women. it is not just a financially elite section of society that gets to make change, but rather it is all of us that have contributed from all socio-economic and cultural backgrounds. those two movements have been incredible at igniting popular discourse and pushing some really difficult conversations into the spotlight, but i think #women taking, and i use that word as opposed to giving, the platforms they deserve can be credited to a multitude of reasons, and a huge one being that weâ€™re no longer willing to swallow silence. weâ€™ve reached such a boiling point of anger, frustration and hurt that weâ€™ve almost snapped. have gone past the point of tiptoeing around societal expectations and are not holding back anymore, and thatâ€™s such a wonderful space to be in. read full interview www.alt-africa.com

text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf
medium

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

text:
what a day. where to start?

after last night 3 people asking me in a q&a if i am pregnant, to waking up to so ma y messages today about so many women and their challenges and how hurtful it was for them to have been asked the same question especially with all their struggles in that area my heart is aching. all of us project. we project our feelings, we project was is going on in our lives and sometimes we assume that others are having a similar experience as we are. unless we personally either say the wrong thing to someone or experience someome saying the wrong thing to us, it is hard to understand why this is not an overly sensitive thing to do by not commenting...its the right thing to do. aside for all this, the body shame that comes along with all this is beyond destructive. why is it that when someone comments on someones body (belly in specific) do some women feel horrible about themselves, some throw that outfit out, some crash diet, some wear a girdle every day, some cry and feel alone and "fat" and even "ugly" when people assume they are pregnant. and many said that after they said very clearly they arent pregnant "are you sure? but you look it" so so many have gotten such remarks! why?! i believe its lack of education. possible a social issue, insecurity. whatever it is, it hurts. women. need to be there to lift eachother up, not knock eachother down, shame. no body was created the same. and it is more than okay to have a belly that is not flat. it is normal. all bodies are beautiful, all womens bodies should be respected and not talked about. curious to hear your thoughts. let's lift eachother up! 
photo @pictureitbyniri

#bodypositivity #bodyshaming #womenempowerment #metoo #spreadawareness #postpartum #love #awareness

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

text:
i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

steve bannon left the wh august last year and q appeared the following october. do you believe in coincidences? church militant, anyone?

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

however - while doing this djt with the brave bunch known as gop has willingly opened a pussy wound that anyone around the world can easily contaminate. i like to call it meddlin' with presidental blessin'. i'm not the only one who knows this opportunity and messes with the boombastic patriots - may be russia or china or mbs or antifa or me me me, a tiny quarter pounder sitting on me me me bed. obviously someone has a lot to lose when none of the us intelligence agencies ends this loonatic travesty.

qshow seems like a vile roleplay but instead it has become the heart of the propaganda operation that joseph goebbels would have died for. it is clear that stuff like pizzagateâ„¢ was testing and groundwork for the 2016 election and since it proved to be very effective it is used still.

the accompanying memes go way beyond the propaganda of nsdap. social media companies are helpless with the content - no way they are going to risk their business by taking responsibility.

there is absolutely no way that gop isn't aware of what is going on - after all cambridge analytica worked for ted cruz and john bolton. the whole narrative is built on the same facebook user data that bannon and the mercers reportedly got from cambridge analytica.

trump is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words. the bigger issue still is that republicans willingly piggybacked this lunacy while campaigning for the midterms and still keep abusing the faith of their fellow men.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.

i've watched the qspiracy since the beginning.

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit a hijacked party is obviously just business as usual.

this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.
